related.description: Spurs forward Tim Duncan left Monday night's game against the Grizzlies with an injured left ankle.
related.linkText: Spurs' Duncan injures ankle vs. Grizzlies
related.title: Spurs' All-Star has Grade 2 sprain
related.headline: Spurs' All-Star has Grade 2 sprain

article.headline: Duncan joins Parker with injured ankle
article.story:
MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- The Memphis Grizzlies took advantage when San Antonio lost Tim Duncan to an injury. Stromile Swift scored five points in the final minutes and finished with 14 points and eight rebounds to lead Memphis to an 88-80 victory over the injury-plagued Spurs on Monday night. San Antonio, already missing starting point guard Tony Parker because of an ankle injury, lost Duncan with five minutes remaining in the first quarter with a minor ankle sprain. Then, coach Gregg Popovich was ejected in the second quarter. The Grizzlies knew they needed to capitalize. "When Tim went down, we all looked at each other and said: 'We've got to win this game,' " said Memphis center Lorenzen Wright, who finished with nine rebounds. "...(Retired) David Robinson is not there any more, so when Tim goes down, that's your opportunity to beat them." The team described Duncan's injury as a mild sprain to the left ankle and said last season's league MVP would have an MRI on Tuesday. Duncan, who had 10 first-quarter points, appeared to roll his foot after a shot. He fell near the foul line and held his ankle before time was called. After team officials looked at the injury, Duncan limped to the bench and eventually to the dressing room. "When you lose the MVP, it changes what you do because a lot of our menu revolves around Tim," said Spurs assistant P.J. Carlesimo, who took over the team after Popovich's ejection. Jason Williams had 13 points and seven assists for the Grizzlies, who earned their first home win over San Antonio since moving to Memphis three years ago. Wesley Person and Earl Watson added 12 points each in reserve roles. Rasho Nesterovic and Manu Ginobili scored 13 apiece for the Spurs, who have lost both their road games this season. Nesterovic grabbed 14 rebounds, and Ron Mercer and Malik Rose finished with 10 points each. San Antonio led 78-76 with 2:30 remaining. But Memphis shot 8-for-10 from the line down the stretch, and Swift scored five points in the last two minutes to fuel the Grizzlies' comeback. "For us, down the stretch, we finally had some urgency," said Memphis coach Hubie Brown. "We stopped them seven of the last eight times. Also, in the last quarter we made our foul shots." Memphis overcame turnovers and poor shooting in the first half, and used a 22-foot jumper by Williams to take a 45-44 lead at the break. Memphis maintained its lead through the third period and held a 64-62 advantage entering the final period. By all accounts, it was an ugly game. The Spurs committed 24 turnovers to 18 for Memphis. San Antonio shot 38 percent, only slightly better than the 37 percent by Memphis. Both sides said defense caused the sloppy play. "They're an aggressive defensive team. They are the world champs," Wright said. "People want to underestimate them when Tim Duncan goes down. "Most definitely, they are a different team. They are going to lose some scoring, but that's not going to stop them from playing defense. That's what they do. That's why they win championships." Game notes
Spurs coach Gregg Popovich said Parker would not play Tuesday against the Heat and was doubtful for Thursday against the Lakers. "Everybody's got injured guys at some point. You don't even think about it, but it's a little difficult since our first, second and third string point guards are gone." ... Popovich was ejected early in the second quarter when he charged onto the court to argue a call. He had to be restrained by his assistants. ... The Spurs handed the Grizzlies their only loss in the preseason. ...The win gives Memphis (2-1) its first regular season winning record since a 4-1 start in 2000-01. ...Prior to Monday, the last Grizzlies home win over the Spurs was in November, 1996.
